</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The term <i>vasculitis</i> includes a variable group of entities in which the common characteristic is inflammation of the walls of blood vessels occurring at some time during the course of the disease. The vasculitides can be divided into primary and secondary vasculitides, depending on the etiology and according to the size of the vessel affected. Both primary vasculitis and secondary vasculitis are associated with cardiac morbidity that is often subclinical. Cardiac involvement is associated with prognostic implications and higher rates of related mortality. Vasculitis of cardiac structures and the assessment of disease extent are important for appropriate management and selection of treatment. Although echocardiography, radionuclide imaging, and catheter-directed coronary angiography remain the cornerstones of cardiac imaging, cardiac computed tomography and magnetic resonance imaging can offer a 360° assessment of cardiac anatomy, function, and complications secondary to vasculitis. Postoperative complications, which are more frequent in patients with active disease, can also be depicted with those imaging modalities. A multidisciplinary approach is important to yield an appropriate estimate of the disease activity and extent and, therefore, to enable better treatment selection and monitoring.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170136">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018170136">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig1.jpeg" height="1477" width="3715" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Revised Chapel Hill Consensus Conference criteria (2012) for vasculitis. Blue lettering indicates those vasculitides with possible cardiac involvement. <i>ANCA</i> = antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibody, <i>GBM</i> = glomerular basement membrane, <i>Ig</i> = immunoglobulin. (Adapted and reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r1" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r1">1</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig2a.jpeg" height="1487" width="1481" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Incidentally detected aortic aneurysm in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast material–enhanced chest CT angiographic image at the level of the ascending aorta shows marked aortic wall thickening, areas of calcification, and aneurysmal dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced chest CT angiographic image at the origin of the coronary arteries shows effacement of the sinotubular junction and involvement of the coronary artery origins with coronary artery encasement. The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed an inflammatory infiltrate centered at the vasa vasorum, with vague granuloma formation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig2b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1469" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Incidentally detected aortic aneurysm in a 63-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast material–enhanced chest CT angiographic image at the level of the ascending aorta shows marked aortic wall thickening, areas of calcification, and aneurysmal dilatation. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced chest CT angiographic image at the origin of the coronary arteries shows effacement of the sinotubular junction and involvement of the coronary artery origins with coronary artery encasement. The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed an inflammatory infiltrate centered at the vasa vasorum, with vague granuloma formation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig3.jpeg" height="1338" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Giant cell arteritis in a patient who was initially suspected of having vasculitis after lung cancer chemotherapy. Axial FDG PET/MR image shows high radiotracer uptake (arrows) in the wall of the ascending and descending aorta, a finding that indicates active disease. (Case courtesy of Prabhakar Rajiah, MD, University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center, Dallas, Tex.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig4.jpeg" height="2564" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Takayasu arteritis in a 30-year-old woman. Coronal contrast-enhanced whole-body MR angiographic image shows involvement of both subclavian arteries (arrows), as well as the combination of stenosis and aneurysms (“string of pearls” sign) in the abdominal aorta (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig5.jpeg" height="1396" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and eosinophilic myocarditis in a 61-year-old man with chronic asthma who presented with dyspnea and an elevated serum level of troponin. The findings at cardiac catheterization were normal. The eosinophil count was elevated at 5200/L (5200 × 10<sup>9</sup>/L), and the results of examination of a bone marrow aspirate yielded 21% eosinophils. This four-chamber late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a diffuse subendocardial enhancement pattern that also involves the right ventricle and both atrioventricular valves. An apical intracardiac thrombus is also depicted. The diagnosis was eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and eosinophilic myocarditis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig6.jpeg" height="1470" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. Pericardial, pleural, and predominantly extrapleural involvement in a patient with Erdheim-Chester disease. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows the involvement of the epicardial fat surrounding the right atrium and the right atrioventricular roof, with secondary right coronary artery encasement (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig7a.jpeg" height="1597" width="1633" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Coronary artery encasement in a 68-year-old man with a remote history of liver transplantation, who presented with fatigue. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and sagittal short-axis SSFP MR image <b>(b)</b> show coronary artery encasement (arrow) secondary to IgG4-related disease. (Case courtesy of Dhiraj Baruah, MBBS, MD, Medical College of Wisconsin, Milwaukee, Wis.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig7b.jpeg" height="1597" width="1317" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Coronary artery encasement in a 68-year-old man with a remote history of liver transplantation, who presented with fatigue. Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image <b>(a)</b> and sagittal short-axis SSFP MR image <b>(b)</b> show coronary artery encasement (arrow) secondary to IgG4-related disease. (Case courtesy of Dhiraj Baruah, MBBS, MD, Medical College of Wisconsin, Milwaukee, Wis.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig8.jpeg" height="1977" width="1285" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Fusiform aneurysms in a 21-year-old man with known Kawasaki disease who underwent follow-up evaluation with coronary CT angiography. CT angiographic image shows fusiform aneurysms (arrows) in the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery and the proximal right coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig9.jpeg" height="1569" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Pulmonary artery aneurysm in a patient with a histopathologic diagnosis of giant cell arteritis. Axial contrast-enhanced chest CT image at the level of the main pulmonary artery shows an 8.5-cm pulmonary artery aneurysm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig10a.jpeg" height="1465" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Takayasu arteritis in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced three-dimensional MR angiographic maximum intensity projection image of the thoracic aorta shows mild stenosis of the subclavian arteries and aneurysmal dilatation (arrow) of the proximal segment of the right subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Curved multiplanar reconstruction of contrast-enhanced three-dimensional MR angiographic dataset for the abdominal aorta shows a long stenotic segment in the infrarenal abdominal aorta, interspersed with aneurysmal dilatation, a finding known as the string of pearls sign (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig10b.jpeg" height="1465" width="775" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Takayasu arteritis in a 30-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced three-dimensional MR angiographic maximum intensity projection image of the thoracic aorta shows mild stenosis of the subclavian arteries and aneurysmal dilatation (arrow) of the proximal segment of the right subclavian artery. <b>(b)</b> Curved multiplanar reconstruction of contrast-enhanced three-dimensional MR angiographic dataset for the abdominal aorta shows a long stenotic segment in the infrarenal abdominal aorta, interspersed with aneurysmal dilatation, a finding known as the string of pearls sign (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig11a.jpeg" height="1311" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Long-standing giant cell arteritis and elevation of inflammatory biomarkers in a 54-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood STIR MR image shows mild concentric wall thickening of the descending aorta (arrow) with edema indicative of active disease. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR imaging constitutes a new imaging modality for evaluation of cardiovascular edema. <b>(b)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image obtained with a high <i>b</i> value (<i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows hyperintensity of the aortic wall (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map shows hypointensity of the vessel wall (arrow<b>)</b>, a finding that represents restriction of water motion owing to vessel wall inflammation. Although the data are contradictory, some investigators support the use of edema-sensitive pulse sequences in patients with large vessel vasculitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig11b.jpeg" height="1335" width="1503" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Long-standing giant cell arteritis and elevation of inflammatory biomarkers in a 54-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood STIR MR image shows mild concentric wall thickening of the descending aorta (arrow) with edema indicative of active disease. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR imaging constitutes a new imaging modality for evaluation of cardiovascular edema. <b>(b)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image obtained with a high <i>b</i> value (<i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows hyperintensity of the aortic wall (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map shows hypointensity of the vessel wall (arrow<b>)</b>, a finding that represents restriction of water motion owing to vessel wall inflammation. Although the data are contradictory, some investigators support the use of edema-sensitive pulse sequences in patients with large vessel vasculitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig11c.jpeg" height="1335" width="1445" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Long-standing giant cell arteritis and elevation of inflammatory biomarkers in a 54-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial black-blood STIR MR image shows mild concentric wall thickening of the descending aorta (arrow) with edema indicative of active disease. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR imaging constitutes a new imaging modality for evaluation of cardiovascular edema. <b>(b)</b> Axial diffusion-weighted MR image obtained with a high <i>b</i> value (<i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows hyperintensity of the aortic wall (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map shows hypointensity of the vessel wall (arrow<b>)</b>, a finding that represents restriction of water motion owing to vessel wall inflammation. Although the data are contradictory, some investigators support the use of edema-sensitive pulse sequences in patients with large vessel vasculitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig12.jpeg" height="1635" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Drawings show the evolution of secondary aortic valve involvement in large vessel vasculitis (<a href="#r3" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r3">3</a>). <i>TAK</i> = Takayasu arteritis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig13.jpeg" height="1349" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. Takayasu arteritis and ischemic dilated cardiomyopathy secondary to coronary vasculitis (right and circumflex coronary arteries) in a 30-year-old woman. Four-chamber late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a transmural scar (arrow) in the basal and midventricular lateral segments of the left ventricle.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig14.jpeg" height="1607" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Kawasaki disease in a 3-year-old boy. Oblique nonenhanced three-dimensional T1-weighted black-blood MR angiographic multiplanar reconstruction centered on the left coronary artery shows segmental ectasia of the left coronary artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig15.jpeg" height="1532" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Kawasaki disease in an 11-year-old boy. Nonenhanced bright-blood MR angiographic curved multiplanar reconstruction of the left anterior descending coronary artery shows a fusiform aneurysm (arrow) in the proximal segment of the artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig16a.jpeg" height="1507" width="1502" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and myocarditis (endomyocarditis) in a 33-year-old woman with a history of severe asthma who presented with chest pain, depressed left ventricular function, elevated troponin levels, and eosinophilia of 27%. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber STIR MR image shows myocardial edema in a diffuse subendocardial pattern (arrows). <b>(b)</b> First-pass myocardial perfusion MR image at the midventricular level shows a diffuse subendocardial hypoperfusion indicative of microvascular disease. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image at the midventricular level shows diffuse enhancement of the subendocardium (arrows), a finding in keeping with endomyocardial fibrosis. After a myocardial biopsy, a diagnosis of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and myocarditis (endomyocarditis) was established. The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed increased chronic inflammatory cells, foci of perivascular eosinophilic microabscesses, and areas in which the eosinophils extend within the myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig16b.jpeg" height="1563" width="1479" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and myocarditis (endomyocarditis) in a 33-year-old woman with a history of severe asthma who presented with chest pain, depressed left ventricular function, elevated troponin levels, and eosinophilia of 27%. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber STIR MR image shows myocardial edema in a diffuse subendocardial pattern (arrows). <b>(b)</b> First-pass myocardial perfusion MR image at the midventricular level shows a diffuse subendocardial hypoperfusion indicative of microvascular disease. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image at the midventricular level shows diffuse enhancement of the subendocardium (arrows), a finding in keeping with endomyocardial fibrosis. After a myocardial biopsy, a diagnosis of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and myocarditis (endomyocarditis) was established. The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed increased chronic inflammatory cells, foci of perivascular eosinophilic microabscesses, and areas in which the eosinophils extend within the myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig16c.jpeg" height="1563" width="1475" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and myocarditis (endomyocarditis) in a 33-year-old woman with a history of severe asthma who presented with chest pain, depressed left ventricular function, elevated troponin levels, and eosinophilia of 27%. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber STIR MR image shows myocardial edema in a diffuse subendocardial pattern (arrows). <b>(b)</b> First-pass myocardial perfusion MR image at the midventricular level shows a diffuse subendocardial hypoperfusion indicative of microvascular disease. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image at the midventricular level shows diffuse enhancement of the subendocardium (arrows), a finding in keeping with endomyocardial fibrosis. After a myocardial biopsy, a diagnosis of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis and myocarditis (endomyocarditis) was established. The findings at histopathologic examination disclosed increased chronic inflammatory cells, foci of perivascular eosinophilic microabscesses, and areas in which the eosinophils extend within the myocardium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig17a.jpeg" height="1504" width="1522" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Hypocomplementemic urticarial vasculitis in a 57-year-old man who underwent cardiac MR imaging because of a concern about pericardial or myocardial involvement. Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber <b>(b)</b> gadolinium-enhanced MR images show a patchy focus of mesocardial enhancement (arrow) in the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle at the base. No associated motion abnormality was noted with cine sequences. This finding is probably the result of secondary myocardial damage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig17b.jpeg" height="1504" width="1432" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Hypocomplementemic urticarial vasculitis in a 57-year-old man who underwent cardiac MR imaging because of a concern about pericardial or myocardial involvement. Short-axis <b>(a)</b> and two-chamber <b>(b)</b> gadolinium-enhanced MR images show a patchy focus of mesocardial enhancement (arrow) in the inferolateral wall of the left ventricle at the base. No associated motion abnormality was noted with cine sequences. This finding is probably the result of secondary myocardial damage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig18a.jpeg" height="1381" width="1552" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Chronic pericardial effusion in a 58-year-old woman with rheumatoid arthritis (same patient as in Movies 2 and 3). <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber T1-weighted spectral presaturation with inversion recovery (SPIR) MR image shows a hyperintense pericardial effusion (arrow), representing high protein content. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image depicts enhancement of the pericardial layers caused by active inflammation. The irregular enhancement of the visceral pericardium (arrow) is due to rheumatoid nodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig18b.jpeg" height="1381" width="1598" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Chronic pericardial effusion in a 58-year-old woman with rheumatoid arthritis (same patient as in Movies 2 and 3). <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber T1-weighted spectral presaturation with inversion recovery (SPIR) MR image shows a hyperintense pericardial effusion (arrow), representing high protein content. <b>(b)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image depicts enhancement of the pericardial layers caused by active inflammation. The irregular enhancement of the visceral pericardium (arrow) is due to rheumatoid nodules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig19a.jpeg" height="1404" width="1429" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease in a 51-year-old female smoker with rheumatoid arthritis, hypercholesterolemia, and a history of episodes of pericarditis. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis cine balanced SSFP MR images obtained in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show akinesia, mainly of the inferior and inferolateral wall of the left ventricle, and severe hypokinesia of the inferoseptal segment. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis early gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a diffuse subendocardial rimlike hypoperfusion (arrows), a finding in keeping with microvascular disease. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial and transmural enhancement (arrow) of ischemic origin. This patient has a coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease. In these patients, smoking constitutes the most consistently demonstrated risk factor for rheumatoid vasculitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig19b.jpeg" height="1404" width="1528" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease in a 51-year-old female smoker with rheumatoid arthritis, hypercholesterolemia, and a history of episodes of pericarditis. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis cine balanced SSFP MR images obtained in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show akinesia, mainly of the inferior and inferolateral wall of the left ventricle, and severe hypokinesia of the inferoseptal segment. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis early gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a diffuse subendocardial rimlike hypoperfusion (arrows), a finding in keeping with microvascular disease. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial and transmural enhancement (arrow) of ischemic origin. This patient has a coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease. In these patients, smoking constitutes the most consistently demonstrated risk factor for rheumatoid vasculitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig19c.jpeg" height="1354" width="1463" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. Coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease in a 51-year-old female smoker with rheumatoid arthritis, hypercholesterolemia, and a history of episodes of pericarditis. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis cine balanced SSFP MR images obtained in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show akinesia, mainly of the inferior and inferolateral wall of the left ventricle, and severe hypokinesia of the inferoseptal segment. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis early gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a diffuse subendocardial rimlike hypoperfusion (arrows), a finding in keeping with microvascular disease. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial and transmural enhancement (arrow) of ischemic origin. This patient has a coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease. In these patients, smoking constitutes the most consistently demonstrated risk factor for rheumatoid vasculitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig19d.jpeg" height="1354" width="1486" aria-labelledby="fig19d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span>. Coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease in a 51-year-old female smoker with rheumatoid arthritis, hypercholesterolemia, and a history of episodes of pericarditis. <b>(a, b)</b> Short-axis cine balanced SSFP MR images obtained in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show akinesia, mainly of the inferior and inferolateral wall of the left ventricle, and severe hypokinesia of the inferoseptal segment. <b>(c)</b> Short-axis early gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows a diffuse subendocardial rimlike hypoperfusion (arrows), a finding in keeping with microvascular disease. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image shows subendocardial and transmural enhancement (arrow) of ischemic origin. This patient has a coronary rheumatoid angiitis with a myocardial infarct and microvascular disease. In these patients, smoking constitutes the most consistently demonstrated risk factor for rheumatoid vasculitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig19d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig20a.jpeg" height="1302" width="1518" aria-labelledby="fig20a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span>. Systemic lupus erythematosus associated with antiphospholipid syndrome, pleuritis, and autoimmune myopericarditis in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis STIR MR image shows edema (arrow) of the pericardial layers. <b>(b, c)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(c)</b> show the edematous changes (arrow) of the pericardium, as well as myocardial edema in the lateral and inferior midventricular segments of the left ventricle, a finding not seen at STIR MR imaging. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image depicts enhancement of the pericardium, a finding indicative of active disease (pericarditis sicca), and also shows nonischemic midmyocardial focal enhancement secondary to myocardial inflammation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig20b.jpeg" height="1302" width="1432" aria-labelledby="fig20b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span>. Systemic lupus erythematosus associated with antiphospholipid syndrome, pleuritis, and autoimmune myopericarditis in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis STIR MR image shows edema (arrow) of the pericardial layers. <b>(b, c)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(c)</b> show the edematous changes (arrow) of the pericardium, as well as myocardial edema in the lateral and inferior midventricular segments of the left ventricle, a finding not seen at STIR MR imaging. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image depicts enhancement of the pericardium, a finding indicative of active disease (pericarditis sicca), and also shows nonischemic midmyocardial focal enhancement secondary to myocardial inflammation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig20c.jpeg" height="1364" width="1502" aria-labelledby="fig20c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span>. Systemic lupus erythematosus associated with antiphospholipid syndrome, pleuritis, and autoimmune myopericarditis in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis STIR MR image shows edema (arrow) of the pericardial layers. <b>(b, c)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(c)</b> show the edematous changes (arrow) of the pericardium, as well as myocardial edema in the lateral and inferior midventricular segments of the left ventricle, a finding not seen at STIR MR imaging. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image depicts enhancement of the pericardium, a finding indicative of active disease (pericarditis sicca), and also shows nonischemic midmyocardial focal enhancement secondary to myocardial inflammation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170136/asset/images/large/rg.2018170136.fig20d.jpeg" height="1364" width="1448" aria-labelledby="fig20d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20d</span>. Systemic lupus erythematosus associated with antiphospholipid syndrome, pleuritis, and autoimmune myopericarditis in a 22-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Short-axis STIR MR image shows edema (arrow) of the pericardial layers. <b>(b, c)</b> Diffusion-weighted MR image (<i>b</i> = 300 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> and corresponding apparent diffusion coefficient map <b>(c)</b> show the edematous changes (arrow) of the pericardium, as well as myocardial edema in the lateral and inferior midventricular segments of the left ventricle, a finding not seen at STIR MR imaging. <b>(d)</b> Short-axis late gadolinium-enhanced MR image depicts enhancement of the pericardium, a finding indicative of active disease (pericarditis sicca), and also shows nonischemic midmyocardial focal enhancement secondary to myocardial inflammation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170136&amp;id=fig20d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Jennette JC, Falk RJ, Bacon PA, et al. 2012 revised International Chapel Hill Consensus Conference nomenclature of vasculitides. <em>Arthritis Rheum</em> 2013;65(1):1–11.</div><div class="external-links"><div class=